Congratulations! You have had at least one mammogram to screen for breast cancer in the past two years. Mammograms are considered the best screening test for breast cancer in women above the age of 40; you should be getting one at least every two years unless otherwise specified by your doctor.

Having a normal BMI (body mass index)

message.message:
According to our records, you have diabetes mellitus (type 1 or type 2). We recognize that diabetes is a complex condition and that its effects on your life are far-reaching. As you know, in diabetes your blood sugar is abnormally elevated, either because your body does not produce insulin (type 1) or because your body does not appropriately respond to insulin (type 2). There is a specific kind of hemoglobin in your blood called hemoglobin A1c (HbA1c), or glycosylated hemoglobin. The percentage of HbA1c in your blood is a measure of your average blood sugar over the past 3 months.

Elevated blood sugar has many effects on your body, including:

  • Eye damage (diabetic retinopathy)
  • Kidney damage (diabetic nephropathy)
  • Nerve damage (diabetic neuropathy)
  • Increased blood pressure (hypertension)

While nerve damage cannot be screened for, eye damage, kidney damage, and increased blood pressure can. By keeping your blood sugar within the target range, and making sure that appropriate screening is done for eye damage, kidney damage, and increased blood pressure, you can minimize the negative effects that diabetes can have on your life over time.

According to our records:

  • You have never had a Hemoglobin A1c (HbA1c) test. As such, we recommend that you talk to your doctor about getting one. Having an HbA1c test done is a critical part of your diabetes management, and we encourage you to get the best care for your condition.
  • You have not yet had a retinal exam this year. As such, we recommend that you get one done. Most optometry offices have the capability of doing this, as do all ophthalmology offices. Getting an annual retinal exam is especially important for those with diabetes, as elevated blood sugar over time can lead to permanent eye damage (even resulting in blindness).
  • You are not being adequately monitored and/or managed for diabetes-related kidney damage (diabetic nephropathy). As such, we recommend that you talk to your doctor about best next steps. Kidney damage is unfortunately common in those with diabetes because of the blood vessel damage that having high blood sugar causes. Being appropriately monitored (and managed, if kidney damage exists) is therefore very important to both your quality of life and your overall diabetes journey.
  • You have never had a blood pressure measurement after your diabetes diagnosis. As such, we recommend that you talk to your doctor about getting one. Because of the blood vessel damage that having high blood sugar causes, high blood pressure is common in those with diabetes. High blood pressure is a leading cause of cardiovascular disease and stroke, both of which are top-five causes of death in the USA.

message.message: Our records show that you have not yet had a bone density scan to test for osteoporosis. We recommend that you talk to your doctor about possibly getting a bone density scan. Osteoporosis is a weakening of bone that occurs as we age, that can result in serious injury if not stopped. All older adults are at risk for osteoporosis, but postmenopausal women are especially at risk.

message.message:
As we age, our clinical care also changes. Just as immunizations are a major focus of early childhood medical care, there are specific items that become the major focus of medical care for older adults. These items are the following:

  • Advance care planning
  • Medication review
  • Functional status assessment
  • Pain assessment

The best care for you as an older adult is to receive these 4 items on an annual basis. For these items:

  • According to our records, you have not yet had advance care planning this year. If this is the case, we strongly recommend that you have this discussion with your doctor and your family.
    • Advance care planning is extremely important during all stages of life, but becomes extraordinarily important as we near the end of our lives. By participating in advance care planning, you are giving clear directives as to how you wish to be treated, and you are saving your family members from having to make difficult decisions that you may or may not have wanted in the event that you become incapacitated.
    • For more information on advance care planning, please go here.
  • According to our records, you have not yet had a functional status review this year. If this is the case, we strongly recommend that you have this discussion with your doctor.
    • Functional status assessments are a way for your care team to understand exactly what your current capabilities are in being able to perform your activities of daily living without incident. Loss of independence is something that can largely be avoided in older adults, and usage of these assessments is a critical part of the puzzle.
    • For more information on functional status assessments and promoting health in older adults, please go here.
  • According to our records, you have not yet had a pain assessment this year. If this is the case, we strongly recommend that you have this discussion with your doctor.
    • Half of all older adults in the USA have arthritis and some degree of pain secondary to arthritis. Furthermore, a significant portion of the older adults in the USA experience some level of pain due to other conditions they may have. As such, it is important that you be assessed for your current pain level on a yearly basis. You do not have to live with pain in your life - there are interventions that can be of great help in this arena. If you are experiencing pain, it is worth having a discussion with your doctor about what can be done.
    • For more information about pain assessment and pain management in older adults, please go here.
  • According to our records, you have not yet had a medication review this year. If this is the case, we strongly recommend that you have this discussion with your doctor.
    • Older adults have a tendency to be on more medications, and as such older adults are at much higher risk of negative side effects due to the drugs they are taking. As such, it is critical that your medications be reviewed on at least a yearly basis.
    • For more information on medication reviews and adverse drug events in older adults, please go here.

Here at Pluto Health, we hope that all of our patients go on to lead healthy lives - whether they are 7, or 70 years of age. Becoming an older adult does not mean having to give up your independence, or having to live in pain, or having to be on a multitude of medications. Older adults are just as vital a part of the tapestry of the human experience as younger people are, and you have so much to give to the world still. We wish you good health this year - and all the years of your life.

message.message:
Congratulations! According to our records, you are up to date on all of your pneumococcus (if applicable) and influenza vaccinations. Vaccinations are perhaps the most important contributor to the large increase in worldwide life expectancy that occurred in the 20th century. The diseases against which you have been immunized were significant factors in mortality before these immunizations became commonplace.

These two vaccines (pneumococcus and influenza) both protect against serious lung infections. The pneumococcus vaccination generally only needs to be taken once, and the influenza vaccination needs to be taken every year. Pneumococcus vaccination is generally only required for the immunocompromised or for adults over the age 65. The virus responsible for influenza (influenzavirus) mutates significantly every year, making a yearly vaccination necessary. It is especially critical for younger and older patients, and those who have weakened immune systems, to get these vaccinations.

We encourage you to continue to get all of the vaccinations that are recommended to you.

message.message:
According to our records, you (a) have a diagnosis of major depression, and (b) are on an antidepressant medication. We understand the struggle; there is an unwarranted stigma associated with mental health that often prevents patients such as yourself from seeking out and receiving the best possible care. Furthermore, antidepressant medications (like all medications) have their share of side effects. Fortunately, many of these side effects can be appropriately managed with the right interventions.

We want to congratulate you for adhering to your antidepressant drug regimen. That is certainly the best care for you, and we want to commend you for your tenacity. We also want to arm you with resources as you continue on in your health journey:

  • Tools and healthy coping mechanisms for stress and depression
  • Free hotlines and resources for those having mental health issues
  • If you are a healthcare professional struggling with stress/depression due to the COVID-19 pandemic: there's a program specifically for you

message.message:
The following is a recommendation of the United States Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF). It was last reviewed by the Pluto Health Clinical Team in September 2022.

Based on our records, you have not yet had appropriate testing for Hepatitis C Virus (HCV). HCV is a common sexually transmitted virus that can be hard to detect, because it often doesn't cause any symptoms when you first get it. Left untreated, it can cause major liver damage, followed by liver failure. Most cases of HCV are treatable and most HCV patients can be cured, but in some cases it can't be and stays with the patient for the rest of the patient's life ('chronic HCV'). Therefore, it's recommended that you get tested for HCV, as catching it early can affect what happens next for you.

Also, there are several groups of people who have a higher (sometimes much) than average risk of being infected with Hepatitis C Virus. These groups include men who have sex with other men, recreational drug users who inject themselves or who are injected and those who already have a medical condition that weakens their immune systems. It's been shown that people who are in these groups do better when they are regularly checked for Hepatitis C Virus infection. If you happen to belong to one of these groups, we even more strongly encourage you to get regularly screened for Hepatitis C Virus -- it could very well save your life.

HCV testing is a lot like HIV/AIDS testing. It requires two tests: an initial ('screening') test, followed by a final ('confirmatory') test if the initial test is positive. The reason why testing is done this way is to make sure that only those who really have HCV are treated for it. If you do just the initial test, too many people who don't actually have HCV will test positive. If you do just the final test, too many people who actually have HCV will test negative. It's only when both tests are done that you get an accurate final result back.

If you have not yet gotten tested for HCV, we strongly urge you to contact your doctor about getting tested. That is the best care for you, and we have faith that you will continue to take the best care of yourself that you can.

tests.description: An at-home hepatitis C test provides the tools to collect a sample of blood and send it to a laboratory for antibody testing. If hepatitis C antibodies are detected on the at-home test, additional testing must be ordered by a physician to determine if the result is due to a current infection that requires treatment or due to a past infection that has resolved.
